  stem:"Which statement correctly distinguishes the duct epithelium of the eccrine sweat gland from the secretory mechanism of the apocrine sweat gland?",
  summary:"Eccrine (merocrine) sweat glands have a coiled secretory unit lined by clear and dark cells and a duct lined by stratified cuboidal epithelium (two layers of cuboidal cells). Apocrine sweat glands, found in the axilla, areola and perineum, open into hair follicles (not directly onto the surface) and their secretion is discharged by apocrine (decapitation) secretion — the apical cytoplasm buds off with secretory product. Both gland types are surrounded by myoepithelial cells that aid expulsion of secretion.",
